The chief minister of [Haryana](/Haryana) is the [head of government](/Head_of_government) of the Indian state of [Haryana](/Haryana). As stipulated by the [Constitution of India](/Constitution_of_India), the [governor](/Governors_of_states_of_India) holds the position of the state's [de jure](/De_jure) head. However, the [de facto](/De_facto) executive authority is vested in the [chief minister](/Chief_Minister_(India)). Following elections to the [Haryana Legislative Assembly](/Haryana_Legislative_Assembly), the state's governor typically extends an invitation to the political party, or coalition of parties, that commands a majority of seats to form the [government](/Government_of_Haryana). The governor then formally appoints the chief minister, whose [council of ministers](/Cabinet_(government)) is collectively accountable to the assembly. The chief minister's tenure is for a period of five years, contingent upon maintaining the confidence of the assembly, and is not subject to any [term limits](/Term_limit).

Since the formation of Haryana in 1966, eleven individuals have occupied the position of chief minister. The inaugural holder of this office was [Bhagwat Dayal Sharma](/Bhagwat_Dayal_Sharma), who served as a member of the [Indian National Congress](/Indian_National_Congress) party. [Bhajan Lal Bishnoi](/Bhajan_Lal_Bishnoi) holds the record for the longest tenure as Haryana's chief minister, having served for an impressive 11 years and 10 months, which amounts to 4317 days. [Devi Lal](/Devi_Lal), who served as the fifth chief minister of Haryana, later achieved prominence on the national stage, serving twice as [Deputy Prime Minister of India](/Deputy_Prime_Minister_of_India) under the premierships of [V. P. Singh](/V._P._Singh) and [Chandra Shekhar](/Chandra_Shekhar). [Om Prakash Chautala](/Om_Prakash_Chautala) has the distinction of serving the most non-continuous terms as chief minister, a total of four, and notably represented three different political parties during his tenures. The current chief minister, [Nayab Singh Saini](/Nayab_Singh_Saini), assumed office on 12 March 2024, making him the second individual from the [Bharatiya Janata Party](/Bharatiya_Janata_Party) to hold the position.

